Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as eddfc437edfc871b469199552bdeb0d65ee2dcf3

We lose a little search-ability here. I think this is well outweighed by fixing "bad characters are not being encoded correctly" which is what we had using std::string::operator+=. A big change. Might have been good to breaking this up. Oh well. 
The URIs that changed need addressed but overall I am good with this.

yeah, it seems like we prefered using `urlFromPieces` going forward, so I just went ahead and fix the older ones. Also thought about fixing each resource individually, but probably easier to revert is this turns out to be an issue to revert all changes later.

What about getting something in the middle.

We write a function which takes a string literal and a serial of pieces,

The function then construct a URL from the string literal and append the pieces.
yeah, we could. With that, I guess we don't really need the existing  `urlFromPieces` since that one is just one that started with `/`.

I'm ok with a little less searchability here.  We still retain searchability on the BMCWEB_ROUTE instances, which are generally close enough to the odata.id calls that it's a trivially incremental add to get to this.

Arguably, we could've written urlFromPieces as something like fmt, and kept both.

urlFromPieces("/redfish/v1/Chassis/{}/Sensors/{}", chassisId, sensorId)

But that seems like it might have other consequences on complexity.  I'm happy to have that discussion, but not on this patch, which is already taking the pattern we discussed and decided on a long time ago and making it consistent.  Even if we chose to invent another helper function, this commit would still be needed to finish the first migration.

Wish this wasn't in the crow name space, oh well, something we can fix one day. 

https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/commit/eae855c74b30085f6ac1094f6087c6b3913a9a69

Crow arguably should be http these days.  I've avoided doing it because I didn't want to add to all the "going to break everyones downstream commits" piles that we have already.  At some point when those calm down, we can add it to the queue again.

I'll work on this fix.
Fixed it within this change.
For things like this that are entirely static, we normally wouldn't do this, we would just use the string as is, but considering that we need to set the fragment, it seems ok.

This looks incorrect.

StorageControllers/1 is not a URI, it is a fragment, or debatably a json pointer (which we also have a type for).  Considering that there's no way that std::to_string(int) can produce a value that doesn't encode properly, there's not really any reason to avoid string concatenation in this case, and even if we were going to, we would use json_pointer operator/=, not url.

This is the only thing I really have issues with.  If you want to drop this diff to another patch, I suspect this patch as-written can merge, or I'm happy to try to come up with a solution to this json pointer fragment thing in this patch.  Up to you.

Can you please test if this causes bugs with a username like:

"my-user" or "my_user" or "my<unicode character>user".

Currently this is a place where the end user is in control of the URI, so we need to make sure that escaping things isn't going to break anything.

It's not really about unit tests.  This would require an integration test, of which I think there are some in test-automation repo that you could use.  You looked up the characters that get encoded in a URI.  What characters get encoded in a dbus path and pam user?  I'm not sure I know the answer to that without testing.  The example I gave you above are the common ones that folks expect to work, and that should be on the golden path.  I can live with less-than-ideal behavior in the error paths when sending in bad characters, but we need to test the common cases.
